{"id":14881345,"mediaExerciseId":"070622ee-34cb-4c55-83cc-d43e371ff47d","exerciseName":"9","chapterName":"12","chapterTitle":"Some Lessons From Capital Market History","groupId":612362,"groupTitle":"Critical Thinking Questions","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":415,"solutions":[{"id":6138907,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this problem, we need to discuss the Efficient Market Hypothesis and how some investors were able to profit if the EMH theory is true. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"The Efficient Markets Hypothesis indicates that a perfect market is a market wherein the information relevant to the stocks price is available to everyone without cost. This means that there is little to no room for the exploitation of the discrepancies between the initial investment and sale price since thee two values are equal in an efficient market.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"Having these people who have huge returns does not invalidate the EMH theory since profits can still be made from the improvement of a company in their projects. These investors were able to make use of the available information to judge which markets will increase in value in the future, thus having huge returns compared to the other investors. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3}],"rating":0,"solutionUuid":"fcd730e9-03c2-40e1-82da-066b6b3ecfa2","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":3}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2